ce:section.ce:para:
To investigate the UV absorption efficiency of the 3&4A-CDs@CMC films in real situations, UV irradiation meter is used to evaluate the absorption efficiency of the 3&4A-CDs@CMC films as Fig. 8
                        a. The 3&4A-CDs@CMC films were put on the negative carrier and measured residual intensity of UV light. In Fig. 8b–c, as the concentration of doped 3&4A-CDs increases from 0 to 0.45 wt%. The intensity went from 18.940 W/m2 of daylight to 0.315 W/m2 (CMC
                           Ⅰ

                        ) and 1.023 W/m2 (CMCⅤ
                        ) in daylight and 67.725 W/m2 of UV-light to 1.678 W/m2 (CMC
                           Ⅰ

                        ) and 2.025 W/m2 (CMCⅤ
                        ) in UV-light. The absorption efficiency increases from 49.38% to 97.15% (CMC
                           Ⅰ

                        ) and 38.71%–97.45% (CMCⅤ
                        ) in daylight, meanwhile, 39.28%–96.10% (CMC
                           Ⅰ

                        ) and 28.9%–95.34% (CMCⅤ
                        ) in UV-light, respectively. The 0.45 wt% 3&4A-CDs@CMC films can nearly block full UV-light both under the daylight and UV lamp. In addition, as the aging time of 0.45 wt% 3&4A-CDs@CMC films increases from 0 to 150 h in Fig. 8d, the residual intensity went from 1.678 W/m2 to 21.688 W/m2 (CMC
                           Ⅰ

                        ) and 2.025 W/m2 to 22.723 W/m2 (CMCⅤ
                        ), the absorption efficiency increases from 96.10% to 83.51% (CMC
                           Ⅰ

                        ) and 95.34%–82.44% (CMCⅤ
                        ), respectively.
